                    <h2>Static vs Dynamic Signs</h2>
                    <div class="paragraph">
                        <p>In American Sign Language there are two types of signs: Static and Dynamic.</p>
                        <h3>Static</h3>
                        <p> Definition: Static signs in ASL are those that do not involve movement. They are stationary
                            handshapes or gestures. Static signs rely on the use of the shape and direction of your
                            hands and fingers and are typically reserved for letters, numbers, and simple
                            words. This Introductory will primarily focus on these signs.<br> </br>
                            Characteristics: These signs usually involve a specific handshape held in a particular
                            position or location relative to the body, without any change in the handshape or movement
                            of the hands through space.<br> </br>
                            Examples:<br> </br>
                            • The sign for "tree" typically involves an extended arm and fingers to mimic the shape of a
                            tree trunk and branches, held in a stationary position.<br></br>
                            • The sign for "book" often involves holding your hands together as if holding a closed
                            book, without moving them.

                        </p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="paragraph">
                        <h3>Dynamic</h3>
                        <p>Dynamic signs incorporate gestures and movements with shape and direction to symbolize larger
                            words or even strings of them. <br> </br>
                            Definition: Dynamic signs, on the other hand, involve movement. These are signs where the
                            shape, position, or orientation of the hands change during the course of making the sign.
                            <br> </br>

                            Characteristics: These signs may involve moving the hands through space, changing hand
                            orientation, or altering the handshape during the sign. The movement is a critical component
                            of the sign's meaning. <br> </br>

                            Examples: <br> </br>

                            The sign for "to eat" involves moving a handshape towards the mouth.<br></br>
                            The sign for "running" involves a repeated motion with both hands to represent legs moving
                            rapidly. <br> </br>
                        </p>
