    <section class="orientation">
        <h2>Importance of Orientation</h2>
        <p>Imagine you're drawing a picture, but the way you hold your pencil changes what the picture looks like.
            That's kind of how sign language works. In sign language, the way you position your hands, the direction
            they're facing, and where your fingers are can change the meaning of what you're saying, just like different
            pencil strokes change a drawing.<br> </br>
            For instance, in American Sign Language (ASL), there are letters like 'A' and 'S' that look very similar.
            The only difference is where the thumb is placed. This is a bit like how in English, words like 'cat' and
            'bat' sound similar but mean different things because of one letter. In sign language, moving your hand a
            little bit, or changing how a finger is bent, can completely change what the sign means.<br> </br>
            This is why being precise with hand movements in sign language is so important. If you don't use your hands
            and fingers correctly, people might get the wrong message. It's like telling a story with your hands, and
            every detail of your hand movement adds to the story, making it clear and interesting.
            Learning sign language isn't just about knowing a bunch of hand signs; it's about learning a whole new way
            to talk without speaking. Every hand shape, every movement, tells part of the story. And just like learning
            any new language, it takes practice and attention to details.<br> </br>
            For kids and adults alike, understanding this is key to being good at sign language. It's not only useful
            for talking to people who are deaf or hard of hearing but also a fun way to communicate silently, like
            having your own secret code. By paying attention to the small details in how you move your hands, you can
            become really good at this beautiful language.<br> </br>
            Remember, in sign language, every hand movement is like a word in a story. So, when you're signing, think
            about making your story as clear and vivid as possible with your hands. It's a wonderful way to express
            yourself and connect with others in a unique and special way.

        </p>
